postsData.content:
This is so funny, because it's true.

Experimenting with content and getting weird with it has been so much fun!

What's even better is there isn't just one way to make that magic happen.

Now there's doing things randomly and what hits, hits. And that's okay.

Or there's adding measurement to the things you are doing to quantify and understand the elements of what's working, when it works best and who that content lands on....

From there it's extract and amplify your own distilled versions of your truth and what resonates into something truly potent and on target.

At some point it's worthy of doing all this with a connected plan, that leads to a specific destination and end in mind.

Hmm reading back on this, it's exactly the layers of learning that turned into what is now the playbook today for us.


Thanksfor sharing this and everything else you bring to enrich and support the communities you touch!

comments.commentText: I comment on LinkedIn just to make someone's day more exciting :)

postsData.commentAdded: Absolutely love this approach! Embracing experimentation while measuring results is key to unlocking true creativity. Keep inspiring! 🎉

Dr. Josh Ramirez, NPPQ, PMP
Dr. Josh Ramirez, NPPQ, PMP
postsData.content:
Did you know that, based on our estimates, I could post one of the following per day for the next 27,000 years and still not cover all the studies we are currently missing out on applicable to project management? But, we're doing something about it...

A study in Lagos, Nigeria, showed that resource allocation and structured monitoring of project schedules significantly improved healthcare project success. Specifically, 85% of improvements in quality were attributed to scheduled monitoring. This indicates that structured project oversight leads to more efficient healthcare service delivery (Olateju, 2017).
postsData.commentAdded: Incredible insight! Structured oversight truly is a game changer for project success in healthcare. Looking forward to more studies like this!

postsData.content:
This is the hottest GTM role not enough people are talking about. 

It's not an AE, SDR, demand gen person or content marketer. It'll be a GTM/growth ops owner.

Also called: GTM engineer, RevOps Engineer, GTM Ops Engineer, Growth Lead, Growth Strategist, Outbound Architect, or a million & one other things.

They're more comfortable in Clay than Salesforce. Their favorite TLA is ICP, not MQL. And they're well versed in the modern GTM tech stack.

I finally found a  JD for this & it's fromat. (I'm not affiliated, just a fan.)

The TL;DR:

1. They design & orchestrate the end-to-end buyer journey starting with identifying the right ICP & through revenue conversion.

2. They run experiments to find the best possible way to turn ICP accounts into $$.

3. They're well versed in the latest GTM technology & automation tools.

4. They're able to influence other leaders across functions.

5. They're data-driven with an ability to spot problems & identify cost-effective solutions.

You might want to save this JD for later.

comments.commentText:
As you sort of mention in your post, this JD is combining alot of things.

any successful SaaS company in the past 20 years had folks on the team who were responsible for all of this (minus new things like Clay of course). But they were handled by different people. BDRs. RevOps. Enablement. Growth Marketing. etc

I love AI and efficiency and automation as much as the next fella, I just fear that companies might start to assume that all of their revenue problems will be fixed by hiring this single magic GTM unicorn, and I just dont know if a) these people exist, and b) if they can really handle and oversee everything...at high quality(and have the skills / passion / expertise)

Will be interesting to see....

postsData.commentAdded: Absolutely! The GTM growth ops role is a game changer. Excited to see more companies recognizing its value in driving revenue. 💡🚀
